        <div2>
          <head>
            <title type="main">“Fields from Islington to Marybone”</title>
          </head>
          <byline>By <docAuthor>John <name>Adlard</name></docAuthor></byline>
          <p>Blake’s conviction that “The fields from Islington to Marybone, / To Primrose Hill and Saint
John’s Wood” were once “builded over” with Jerusalem’s pillars may have something to do with the fact that
the Order of St. John of Jerusalem (whose Priory Gate still stands in Clerkenwell, adorned with a lamb) once
owned much of this area. St. John’s Wood itself is named after them (there was also a Little St. John’s
Wood in Islington) and Pieter Zwart, in his <hi rend="i">Islington</hi> (London 1973), p. 118, notes that “the
fields to the west” belonged to them.</p>
          <p>London</p>
        </div2>
